# Maintenance of Codenames

When selecting names for methods, files, and
anything else you have influence over its
name, use these naming conventions.

A.  Codename structure
    1.  Use lowercase snake_case with a root
        (leftmost) term defining the broad
        concept.
    2.  Applies to all nameable things: methods,
        functions, classes, files, CSS custom
        properties, IDs, variables, etc.
    3.  Subject: the root term names the subject
        (domain, area, or entity) the codename
        refers to.
        a.  Start a name using an existing root
            when possible.
    4.  Subsequent terms refine object and
        action.
        a.  Object: what is acted on (e.g.
            state_list, card_rect).
        b.  Action: verb last (e.g. _get, _set,
            _build).

B.  Term rules
    1.  Keep terms short and singular.
    2.  Abbreviate frequently used terms.

C.  Codename maintenance
    1.  Engage iteratively to refine
        conventions.
    2.  Keep the index updated for easy sorting.
        a.  List all codenames in index.
        b.  Show count of occurrence listed 36
            characters in.
        c.  Update doc/codename_index.txt every
            time codenames are added, removed,
            or changed.
    3.  Create/maintain codenames.
        a.  Iteratively, in related groups, add
            commented lines with a
            double-underscore before the
            codename related to that code.
    4.  When creating or renaming a method,
        function, or variable, name it per
        section A and add it to the index.

D.  Name index (doc/codename_index.txt)
    1.  Keep lexicographic order by name.
    2.  Insert blank line when root term changes
        (first term before `_`).
    3.  Use `name : type` format.
    4.  Align `:` column vertically.
    5.  Keep `type` short and lowercase (`css`,
        `class`, `id`, `file`, `image`,
        `domain`, `section`, `field`,
        `method`, `function`, `var`).
